The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Patni Computer Systems Ltd has allotted 38,600 shares of Rs 2 each on a par under the employees? stock option (Esop) scheme. The compensation committee of directors took a decision to this effect on March 31, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. The resolution said 38,600 shares of par value of Rs 2 each have been allotted to certain employees of the company under the stock option plan 2003.

 Vestas RRB India, an Indo-Danish venture in the wind energy sector, has inaugurated a facility to manufacture control panels for wind electric generators in Chennai. The company will invest Rs 30 crore to set up another plant for making wind farm blades. The control panel plant will have a capacity to manufacture 400 controllers per annum, which was sufficient to meet a demand for generating 200 MW, managing director Rakesh Bakshi said.

 National Aluminium Company (Nalco) exported products worth Rs 2,200 crore in 2004-05 compared with Rs 1,717 crore last year. According to company officials, Nalco produced the highest-ever alumina of 15.75 lakh tonnes compared with 15.56 lakh tonnes in the previous year. Nalco has sold 2.05 lakh tonnes of metal, up from 1.66 lakh tonnes in the previous year.

 Shree Cement Limited will commission its greenfield plant in Rajasthan in September. The company will invest around Rs 300 crore in the new plant, which would add another 1.3 million tonnes to the existing capacity. During March 2005, the company despatched 2,93,557 tonnes of cement, representing a growth of 12.17 per cent over the year-ago period. 

 Pailan Group has made a foray into the area of food processing. The group will set up a state-of-the-art, 100 per cent export-oriented food processing plant at Dhaniakhali in Hooghly in joint venture with AFT/PB Conseil of France. The foundation stone for the first phase of the Rs 150-crore project will be laid on April 15.

